%[text] %[text:anchor:H_5774] ## VSC-HVDC Admittance Scan and Stability Analysis 
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] This project shows how to detect instabilities in a voltage-source converter high-voltage direct current (VSC-HVDC) system using an impedance scanning technique.
%[text] The HVDC system has two converter stations connected by DC transmission lines that enable power transfer between the two remote locations.
%[text] This project demonstrates how to:
%[text] - Perform admittance scanning (D, Q, DC) for a two-terminal VSC-HVDC system.
%[text] - Construct the full multivariable admittance matrix.
%[text] - Use the generalized Nyquist Criterion (GNC) to evaluate system stability.
%[text] - This frequency-domain stability analysis incorporates both AC- and DC-side dynamics to identify potential resonances and control interactions that may compromise system performance. To validate the frequency-domain stability assessment, you perform a time-domain simulation under a small disturbance scenario and compare the results. \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_361f] ### **System Description**
%[text] This figure shows the unit test model which contains an offshore wind farm connected to the onshore AC grid through a $\\pm \\;400\\;\\textrm{kV}${"editStyle":"visual"} VSC-HVDC network. 
%[text] ![](text:image:3a9b)
%[text] - The VSC-HVDC network consists of onshore and offshore HVDC stations connected through 125 km long bipolar HVDC cables.
%[text] - The wind turbines connect to the offshore wind farm using fully-rated back-to-back converters.
%[text] - The wind farm has an installed capacity of 160 MW, where each wind turbine can generate a rated power of 18 MW at a wind speed of 11 m/s.
%[text] - The offshore converter is grid-forming, while the onshore VSC is grid-following with DC-voltage control and PLL-based synchronization. \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_4a7d] ### Admittance Scan Tool
%[text] This tool determines the frequency vs admittance characteristics of the grid-connected system using only measurements from the point of interconnection (POI). 
%[text] These admittance characteristics are valid for the operating condition over which you estimate the admittance. This tool estimates the admittance in the D-Q frame. 
%[text] This system of equations defines the relationship between the admittance of an Inverter-based resource (IBR), $Y$, perturbed voltages at POI, $\\Delta V${"editStyle":"visual"}, and the perturbed currents, $\\Delta i${"editStyle":"visual"}, along the D and Q axis are given below.
%[text]{"align":"center"} ![](text:image:4ac4)
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{cc}\nY\_{\\textrm{dd}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{dq}} \\\\\nY\_{\\textrm{qd}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{qq}} \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack \\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{c}\n{\\Delta V}\_d \\\\\n{\\Delta V}\_q \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack =\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{c}\n{\\Delta i}\_d \\\\\n{\\Delta i}\_q \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text]{"align":"center"} 
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_2004] ## Admittance Scan of VSC-HVDC based Offshore Wind Farm
%[text] This figure shows how the admittance scan is performed for the HVDC network with the AC-side scan block and DC-side scan block.
%[text] The AC admittance scan block has a phase-locked loop (PLL) that tracks the steady-state grid frequency and converts the measured voltages and currents into their respective D and Q components. 
%[text] The block captures the measured voltages and currents from the AC side and DC side. 
%[text] Similarly, the DC admittance scan block injects a pseudorandom binary sequence (PRBS) voltage disturbance on the DC side and captures the measured voltages and currents from the AC and DC sides. 
%[text] 
%[text] ![](text:image:48df)
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_1dfc] #### **Benefits of Scan Including DC-Side Dynamics** 
%[text] - Using only DQ admittance modeling ignores the effects of the AC network on the DC terminals and vice-versa.
%[text] - The interactions between the AC and DC sides can introduce additional dynamics and potential instability, particularly if there are resonances or adverse interactions that are not accounted for in the system design.  \
%[text] This work performs stability assessment by performing admittance scan on both AC and DC sides of the HVDC stations.
%[text] Considering the interaction between the DC-side and AC-side dynamics, the  relationship among the admittance, perturbed voltages, and currents along the D- and Q-axis are given below.
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{ccc}\nY\_{\\textrm{dd}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{dq}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{dDc}} \\\\\nY\_{\\textrm{qd}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{qq}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{qDc}} \\\\\nY\_{\\textrm{Dcd}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{Dcq}}  & Y\_{\\textrm{Dc}} \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack \\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{c}\n{\\Delta V}\_d \\\\\n{\\Delta V}\_q \\\\\n{\\Delta V}\_{\\textrm{dc}} \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack =\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{c}\n{\\Delta i}\_d \\\\\n{\\Delta i}\_q \\\\\n{\\Delta i}\_{\\textrm{dc}} \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_553e] ## **Steps for Scanning**
%[text] The goal is to extract frequency-domain small-signal models (admittance) of each converter station in the VSC-HVDC system under normal operating conditions. 
%[text] You can use these admittance models to analyze control interactions and assess stability.
%[text] This figure shows how to perform stability assessment for the HVDC system, using admittance scan.
%[text]  **STEP 1** **STEP 2** **STEP 3**
%[text] ![](text:image:24ec)
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_43b3] ### **Step 1: Inject Disturbance and Capture Voltage and Current Signals**
%[text] - First, scan on the AC side of the network by injecting a PRBS voltage disturbance along the D- and Q-axis using the AC Scan block.
%[text] - You measure the perturbed voltages and currents from the AC and DC buses using the AC Scan block and store the measured voltages and currents in the workspace variable, `dataAC`.
%[text] - Similarly, you perform the scanning on the DC side by injecting a voltage disturbance on the DC bus and measure the perturbed voltages and currents from the AC and DC buses using the DC Scan block, and store them as workspace variable, `dataDc`. \
mdl = "HVDCScan"; % HVDC model
open_system(mdl); % Load the model
% Scan block parameters
scan.f = unique([0.5:0.25:20, 21:1:100, 102:2:500, 505:5:3e3]); % Refined: 0.25 Hz steps in 0.5-20 Hz, 1 Hz in 20-100 Hz, coarser above
scan.samplingfrequency = 2e4; % Sampling frequency for scan (Hz)
scan.end = 6; % Time to end frequency scan (s)
scan.start = 2; % Time to start frequency scan (s)
Tsim = scan.end + 0.2; % Simulation run time (s)    
time.wind = Tsim + 1; % Time for switching event (s)
time.load = Tsim + 1;
% Grid impedance
Rs = 0.1; % Resistance (Ohms)
Ls = 29.7e-3; % Inductance (H)
save_system(mdl);
axis1 = ["D-axis","Q-axis","DC"]; % Sequence of axes for each scan in turn
%%
%[text]  **Set Parameters for Scanning On-shore Converter Station and run Parallel Simulations**
%[text]  Define the disturbance injection parameters like the frequency vector, magnitude of PRBS disturbance and time of injection using the custom [`setSimulationforScan`](file:./setSimulationforScan.m) `function.`
% Parameters of PRBS perturbation for scanning onshore station
scan.Vd = 0.001; % Disturbance along D-axis (pu)
scan.Vq = 0.001; % Disturbance along Q-axis (pu)
scan.Vdc = 0.01;% Disturbance along DC-axis (pu)
% Parameters of PRBS perturbation at offshore station during scanning onshore station
scan.Vd1 = 0.0; % Disturbance along D-axis (pu)
scan.Vq1 = 0.0; % Disturbance along Q-axis (pu)
scan.Vdc1 = 0.0;% Disturbance along DC-axis (pu)
% Simulation Setup
inOnShore = setSimulationforScan(mdl,scan,axis1,'VdcKp',20,'VdcKi',1000); % Use model default gains (VdcKp=20, VdcKi=1000)
% Run parallel simulation and collect data
dataScanOnShore = parsim(inOnShore,ShowProgress="off",TransferBaseWorkspaceVariables="on",UseFastRestart="off"); %#ok<*XFRWSP>  %[output:820b880d]
% Validate onshore scan results
for ii = 1:numel(dataScanOnShore)
    if dataScanOnShore(ii).ErrorMessage ~= ""
        error('Onshore scan %d (%s) failed: %s', ii, axis1(ii), dataScanOnShore(ii).ErrorMessage);
    end
end
%%
%[text]  **Set Parameters for Scanning Off-shore Converter Station and run Parallel Simulations**
% Parameters of PRBS perturbation for scanning offshore station
scan.Vd1 = 0.001; % Disturbance along D-axis (pu)
scan.Vq1 = 0.001; % Disturbance along Q-axis (pu)
scan.Vdc1 = 0.01;% Disturbance along DC-axis (pu)
% Parameters of PRBS perturbation at onshore station during scanning of offshore station
scan.Vd = 0.0; % Disturbance along D-axis (pu)
scan.Vq = 0.0; % Disturbance along Q-axis (pu)
scan.Vdc = 0.0;% Disturbance along DC-axis (pu)
% Simulation Setup
inOffShore = setSimulationforScan(mdl,scan,axis1,'VdcKp',1,'VdcKi',1000); % Use model default gains (VdcKp=1, VdcKi=1000)
dataScanOffShore = parsim(inOffShore,ShowProgress="off",TransferBaseWorkspaceVariables="on",UseFastRestart="off"); % Run parallel simulation
% Validate offshore scan results
for ii = 1:numel(dataScanOffShore)
    if dataScanOffShore(ii).ErrorMessage ~= ""
        error('Offshore scan %d (%s) failed: %s', ii, axis1(ii), dataScanOffShore(ii).ErrorMessage);
    end
end
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_6a23] ### **Step 2: Estimate Admittance**
%[text] You estimate the admittance using the functions, `runDCScan`, `runACScan`, from the class [`AdmittanceScanner`](<file:....\Admittance Scan\AdmittanceScanner.m>). 
%[text] Create the objects, `scannerOnShore` and `scannerOffShore`, of this class using the [configureAdmittanceScanner](file:./configureAdmittanceScanner.m) function.
% To create objects of this class you need this configuration field
scannerOnShore = configureAdmittanceScanner(dataScanOnShore, axis1, scan.f);
scannerOffShore = configureAdmittanceScanner(dataScanOffShore, axis1, scan.f);
%[text] You estimate the admittance: $Y\_{\\textrm{dd}}${"editStyle":"visual"}, $Y\_{\\textrm{dq}}${"editStyle":"visual"}, $Y\_{\\textrm{qq}}${"editStyle":"visual"}, $Y\_{\\textrm{qd}}${"editStyle":"visual"}, $Y\_{\\textrm{dDc}}${"editStyle":"visual"}, $Y\_{\\textrm{qDc}}${"editStyle":"visual"} using the  [estimateAdmittances](file:./estimateAdmittances.m)  function on the created objects, `scannerOnShore` and `scannerOffShore`.
% Estimate admittance
YonShore = estimateAdmittances(scannerOnShore); %[output:5722d74d]
YoffShore = estimateAdmittances(scannerOffShore);
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_4864] ### Step 3: VSC-HVDC Stability Analysis using Generalized Nyquist Criterion
%[text] This section performs the stability analysis of the HVDC system using the obtained admittance.
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_2a60] #### Onshore and offshore station admittance
Ylocal = YonShore; % Admittance of onshore VSC (from scanning)
Yremote = YoffShore; % Admittance of offshore VSC (used as load)
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_7765] #### AC Grid Impedance Model in DQ Domain at the Onshore Point of Interconnection
% Define base grid impedance (near the source)
rg = Rs; % Grid resistance (Ohm)
lg = Ls; % Grid inductance (H)
zg = tf([lg rg], 1);  % Grid impedance transfer function

% AC line parameters
lineLength = line.length*2.8; % Line length (km)
rline = line.r*lineLength; % Line resistance (Ohms)
lline =line.l*lineLength* 1e-3; % Line inductance (H)

% Transfer function of line impedance
s = tf('s'); 
zline = (rline + s*lline); % Series impedance (Ohm)
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_0720] **Grid model with Line**
%[text] Equivalent impedance matrix of grid source impedance in DQ Domain:
%[text] You model the AC grid in DQ frame with coupling terms: $Z\_g \\left(s\\right)=\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{cc}\nR\_g +{\\textrm{sL}}\_g  & {j\\omega }\_0 L\_g \\\\\n{-j\\omega }\_0 L\_g  & R\_g +{\\textrm{sL}}\_g \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] Similarly, you model the line impedance in DQ frame with coupling terms: $Z\_{\\textrm{line}} \\left(s\\right)=\\left\\lbrack \\begin{array}{cc}\nZ\_{\\textrm{line}}  & {j\\omega }\_0 L\_{\\textrm{line}} \\\\\n-j{\\omega\_0 L}\_{\\textrm{line}}  & Z\_{\\textrm{line}} \n\\end{array}\\right\\rbrack${"editStyle":"visual"}
omega=2*pi*grid.frequency; % Grid frequency in rad/sec
zGrid = [zg 1j*omega*lg; -1j*omega*lg zg];            % Grid source admittance
zLDQ = [zline 1j*omega*lline; -1j*omega*lline zline]; % Series impedance of line

% The equivalent grid impedance
% Treat: Grid impedance zGrid + line zLine in series
zGridTotal = zGrid + zLDQ;  % Series path: grid + line

% Equivalent impedance from LV-side of the transformer, where scanning is done
zGridEff = zGridTotal*(4.16/230)^2; % POI is on the low voltage side of the 230/4.16 kV transformer
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_5ace] #### **Build Transfer Functions of the DC side Admittance as Seen from Onshore Converter Station**
% DC Cable Parameters (100 km)
lenkm = 120; % Line length (km)
rdcperKm = 9.5e-3; % Resistance (Ohms)
ldcperKm = 2.112e-3; % Inductance (H)
cdcperKm = 0.1906e-6; % Capacitance (F)

% Total DC Line impedance
rdc = rdcperKm * lenkm; % Line resistance (Ohms)
ldc = ldcperKm * lenkm; % Line inductance (Ohms)
cdc = cdcperKm * lenkm; % Line capacitance (Ohms)

% DC cable pi-model: split cable capacitance equally between local and remote ends
% Local end shunt: converter station capacitor + half cable capacitance
% Remote end shunt: half cable capacitance
s = tf('s'); % Transfer function variable
zCable = (rdc + s*ldc);              % Series branch
yshuntLocal  = (HVDC.C + cdc) * s; % Local end: converter cap + half cable cap
yshuntRemote = (cdc) * s;          % Remote end: half cable cap

% Thevenin equivalent of the DC side seen from the onshore converter
YdcEnv = ((Yremote(3,3) + yshuntRemote)/(1 + yshuntRemote*zCable + Yremote(3,3)*zCable)) + yshuntLocal;
%[text] Apply Schur complement to build the admittance model of the VSC at the on-shore station, including the DC-side dynamics.
YVSC1 = YonShore(1:2,1:2) - YonShore(1:2,3) * inv(YonShore(3,3) + YdcEnv) * YonShore(3,1:2); %#ok<MINV>
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_3b1f] #### **Compute the Loop Gain**
L1 = zGridEff*YVSC1;  % Load impedance x Source admittance
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_429f] #### Generalized Nyquist Plot: Eigenvalue Analysis
%w = 2*pi*logspace(log10(1),log10(3e3),2000); % Adjust range as needed
wpos = 2*pi*logspace(0, log10(3e3), 1000);
w = [-fliplr(wpos), wpos];  % Symmetric sweep for closed plot 
%%
% Identify critical margins using Nyquist Plot
generalizedNyquistPlotwithCrossing(L1, w);  % Full symmetric contour for consistent encirclement count %[output:97718d19] %[output:75e24dac]
%%
eigL = encirclementNyquistPlot(L1,w); % Number of encirclement of the critical (-1,0) point %[output:57f8f58e]
%%
%[text] You can observe the generalized Nyquist plot and see that the eigen plots for eigen functions crosses the , -1+0j, at 3.85 H with PM of 8.45 degrees and 3.52 Hz with PM of 54 degrees. These are the gain cross-over frequency at which the system is not adequately damped. 
%[text] **Interpretation of Each Crossing:**
%[text:table]
%[text] | **Frequency** | **Possible Root Cause** |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | <p>**3.83 Hz -ve sequence**</p><p>**3.522 Hz +ve sequence**</p> | Low-frequency band → likely a slow control loop(e.g., PLL, DC-voltage control). |
%[text:table]
%%
bodeDeterminant(eigL, w,scan); % Bode plot of det(I +L(jω)) %[output:78e1005c]
%[text] You observe the **deep notch** in magnitude around ~ 4 Hz.
%[text] The frequencies where ∣det⁡(I+L(jω))∣→0, i.e., the loop transfer function is close to making the determinant zero, which is dangerous for stability.
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_6a1a] #### Bode Plots of Eigen values of \*\*Loop Gain (\*\*L(s))
plotEigLBode(w,eigL,scan); %[output:55b87f8d] %[output:866ccd56] %[output:7c563e01]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_2da1] ## Comparison with Time Domain Simulation
%[text] To validate the frequency-domain stability assessment obtained via generalized Nyquist analysis, a time-domain simulation was performed under a small disturbance scenario. Specifically, a 3 MW change in the load was applied at t = 2 seconds, and the apparent power response of the VSC was analyzed.
scan.Vd = 0.0;  % Disturbance along D-axis (pu)
scan.Vq = 0.0;  % Disturbance along Q-axis (pu)
scan.Vdc = 0.0; % Disturbance along DC-axis (pu)
% Parameters of PRBS perturbation at offshore station during scanning onshore station
scan.Vd1 = 0.0; % Disturbance along D-axis (pu)
scan.Vq1 = 0.0; % Disturbance along Q-axis (pu)
scan.Vdc1 = 0.0;% Disturbance along DC-axis (pu)
% load switch — use longer simulation for better FFT resolution
Tsim = 10; % Time of simulation (s)
time.wind = Tsim + 1;
time.load = 2; % Time of load switch (s)
% Simulation Setup — use model defaults (same as scan: VdcKp=1, VdcKi=1000)
simdata = sim(mdl);
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_9f97] **Collect Post Disturbance Measurements from POI at On-shore Station**
t = simdata.S.Time;           % Time vector
y = squeeze(simdata.S.Data);  % Apparent Power

% Resample to uniform time grid (handles variable-step solver output)
Fs_target = 1e4; % Target sampling frequency (Hz) — well above scan range
t_uniform = (t(1):1/Fs_target:t(end))';
y_uniform = interp1(t, y, t_uniform, 'pchip');

% Trim to post-disturbance window (longer window = finer frequency resolution)
% Window length: Tsim - time.load = 8s → frequency resolution = 0.125 Hz
idxPost = t_uniform >= time.load;
ttrim = t_uniform(idxPost);
ytrim = y_uniform(idxPost);

% Remove mean (DC offset)
ytrim = ytrim - mean(ytrim);

% Time-domain plot (un-normalized)
figure; %[output:81100bbd]
plot(ttrim, y_uniform(idxPost)); %[output:81100bbd]
xlabel("Time (s)"); %[output:81100bbd]
ylabel("Apparent Power (W)"); %[output:81100bbd]
title("Apparent Power at POI") %[output:81100bbd]
xlim([time.load time.load+1]); %[output:81100bbd]
grid on; %[output:81100bbd]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_2ac6] **Plot FFT after Disturbance**
Fs = Fs_target;              % Uniform sampling frequency
N = length(ytrim);           % Number of samples
Y = fft(ytrim);              % Compute FFT

% Frequency vector
f_full = (0:N-1)*(Fs/N);
df = Fs/N; % Frequency resolution

% Remove 60 Hz fundamental and harmonics (up to 10th)
fundamentalFreqs = 60 * (1:10); % 60, 120, 180, ..., 600 Hz
for fk = fundamentalFreqs
    [~, idxk] = min(abs(f_full - fk));
    % Zero out a small band around each harmonic (+/- 2 bins)
    binsToZero = max(1, idxk-2):min(N, idxk+2);
    Y(binsToZero) = 0;
    % Mirror for real-valued signal
    mirrorBins = N - binsToZero + 2;
    mirrorBins = mirrorBins(mirrorBins >= 1 & mirrorBins <= N);
    Y(mirrorBins) = 0;
end

% Single-sided amplitude spectrum (no double normalization)
Y_mag = abs(Y(1:floor(N/2))) / N;  % Scale by N for true amplitude
Y_mag(2:end) = 2 * Y_mag(2:end);   % Double for single-sided (except DC)
f_plot = f_full(1:floor(N/2));

figure; %[output:191cee1b]
plot(f_plot, Y_mag, 'b', 'LineWidth', 0.8); %[output:191cee1b]
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)'); ylabel('Amplitude'); %[output:191cee1b]
title(sprintf('FFT of Apparent Power (df = %.2f Hz, harmonics removed)', df)); %[output:191cee1b]
xlim([0 50]); grid on; % Zoom to 0-50 Hz to see critical low-frequency modes %[output:191cee1b]
%%
%[text] **Zoomed FFT: Full Scan Range**
figure; %[output:5eac7bd7]
plot(f_plot, Y_mag, 'b', 'LineWidth', 0.8); %[output:5eac7bd7]
xlabel('Frequency (Hz)'); ylabel('Amplitude'); %[output:5eac7bd7]
title('FFT of Apparent Power (Full Range, Harmonics Removed)'); %[output:5eac7bd7]
xlim([0 3000]); grid on; %[output:5eac7bd7]
%[text] The post-disturbance signal was resampled to a uniform grid and processed using FFT with a frequency resolution of 0.125 Hz (8-second window). The 60 Hz fundamental and its harmonics (up to 600 Hz) were removed to expose the low-frequency oscillatory modes. 
%[text] The dominant FFT peak which is at 3.5 Hz is align with the critical frequency predicted by the Nyquist analysis (3.5 ~ 3.8 Hz region), where the eigenvalue trajectory approaches the critical point `-1+j0`.
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_3e57] ## Conclusion
%[text] The impedance analysis of the HVDC system based on the DC and AC impedance model is verified with the time-domain simulation  results. The impedance and admittance product is used to evaluate system stability. If the impact of the impedance/ admittance of the DC-side ports are ignored, stability assessment conclusions may have been incorrect.

